data.content:
Two-Envelope Approach
A bidding method where service and price proposals are submitted separately to ensure objective assessment.<SEP>A tender evaluation method where price offers and service proposals are submitted and assessed separately to ensure objective evaluation.

Contractors
External service providers for cleaning and security services that undergo evaluation and selection processes.<SEP>Contractors are service providers who submit quotations and tenders, and are subject to contract terms including performance monitoring and probity clauses.<SEP>Service providers hired by organizations to perform cleaning and security services.<SEP>Contractors are service providers engaged under the contract, required to adhere to specified terms, provide staff lists, duty rosters, and performance records.

Tender Invitation
A formal document used to invite contractors to submit detailed service proposals, with sample provided in Appendix 3.

Designated Authority
A panel or senior staff member responsible for approving contractor shortlists and procurement decisions.<SEP>An authority with the power to approve exceptions, such as accepting late tender submissions under justifiable circumstances.

Tender Box
A secure double-locked container used for receiving physical tender submissions to ensure integrity.<SEP>The physical location where tender documents must be submitted, marked with confidential labeling requirements.

Approved List of Contractors
A maintained list of pre-qualified contractors that meet specific criteria for providing cleaning and security services.

Quotation Invitation
A formal document used to invite contractors to submit price quotes for services, with sample provided in Appendix 2.

Procurement Staff
Procurement Staff are responsible for executing procurement procedures including contractor listing, shortlisting, and bid management.<SEP>Procurement staff are responsible for preparing tender documents, sourcing contractors, and managing various procurement processes.<SEP>Procurement Staff are responsible for checking compliance, evaluating quotations, and managing the procurement process, including documentation and contractor selection.

Quotation/Tender Opening Record
A documented record of all bids received and opened, maintained for audit purposes with sample in Appendix 4.<SEP>A document used to record the receipt and opening of quotations and tenders, serving as an audit trail for the procurement process.<SEP>Sample form used for recording the receipt and opening of quotations or tenders.<SEP>A document that records the details of tender openings, including bidder names and their respective prices, witnessed by authorized personnel.

Cleaning and Security Services
Specific types of services being procured through the outlined contracting processes.

Listing Criteria
Pre-determined standards and procedures for including or removing contractors from the approved list.

Electronic Tendering System
A digital platform used for submitting and managing tender documents.

Site Visit
A potential event arranged for tenderers to visit the service location for better proposal preparation.<SEP>An optional event where tenderers can visit the service location by contacting the designated personnel.

Management
Management establishes procedures with safeguards to prevent tampering of quotations or tenders.<SEP>Management specifies procurement methods, approves tender documents, appoints assessment panels, and supervises procurement processes.<SEP>Management appoints evaluation panels, sets guidelines for post-tender negotiation, and oversees the procurement process to ensure fairness and compliance.<SEP>Management oversees procurement and service quality monitoring processes, arranges audits, initiates investigations, and ensures compliance with policies.

Company/Organization
The Company/Organization is the entity issuing the tender and will be the recipient of the tender submissions and confirmation letters.<SEP>The Company/Organization is the entity requesting services, managing the quotation process, and making purchasing decisions.<SEP>The Company/Organization is the entity issuing the tender invitation and seeking service providers, with specific requirements and submission procedures.

Tenderer
The Tenderer is the entity submitting a bid for the contract and is bound by the rules against collusion in the tendering process.<SEP>The Tenderer is a potential service provider submitting a bid in response to the tender invitation, required to meet eligibility requirements and submit supporting documents.<SEP>Tenderer refers to companies or organizations submitting bids for the contract being tendered.

Confirmation Letter
The Confirmation Letter is a required document that the tenderer must submit, affirming compliance with anti-collusion rules.<SEP>The Confirmation Letter is a required document that must be submitted along with the Form of Tender and supporting documents.

Form of Tender
The Form of Tender is the official document where the tenderer details their offer, including company background, services, and pricing.<SEP>The Form of Tender is a required document that must be completed and signed by the tenderer as part of the submission package.

Tender Invitation Letter
The Tender Invitation Letter outlines the terms and conditions for the tender process and is referenced by the tenderer in their submission.<SEP>Sample letter used for inviting tenders from potential contractors.<SEP>The Tender Invitation Letter is the document that formally requests tenders and includes annexes such as anti-bribery clauses.

Contract
The Contract is the agreement for which the tender is being submitted, specifically for the provision of services.<SEP>The Contract is the formal agreement for the provision of services that is the subject of the tender process.<SEP>The contract is a formal agreement specifying terms and conditions for service provision, including clauses on probity, subcontracting, insurance, and payment claims.

Anti-Collusion Clause
The Anti-Collusion Clause is a rule prohibiting tenderers from communicating or making arrangements with others about their tender.

Excepted Communications
Excepted Communications are confidential discussions allowed with insurers, brokers, consultants, or sub-contractors for tender preparation.

Employer
The Employer is the entity, synonymous with the Company/Organization, that is issuing the tender and will be the recipient of the services.<SEP>The Employer is the entity issuing the tender invitation and is not obligated to accept the lowest or any tender received.

Services
The Services are the specific provisions detailed in the Form of Tender that the successful tenderer will supply to the Employer.<SEP>Services refer to the work to be performed by Provider for Client as described in a Service Order.

Hong Kong Dollars
Hong Kong Dollars is the specified currency in which the tender sum must be offered for the contract.

Prevention of Bribery Ordinance
The Prevention of Bribery Ordinance is a legal document that prohibits offering advantages to staff members in connection with quotations or service provision.

Quotation Form
The Quotation Form is a document that contractors must fill out and submit, containing company information, service details, and pricing.

Invitation Document
The Invitation Document contains Terms of Quotation and serves as the basis for contractors to submit their quotations.

Tender Opening Record
The Tender Opening Record is referenced in Appendix 4 and contains details of quotations/tenders received.

data.content:
Sample Form for Invitation of Quotation
This is a sample document template used to formally request quotations from contractors for services.

data.entity_name: Sample Letter for Invitation of Tender
data.content:
Sample Letter for Invitation of Tender
This is a sample letter template used to formally invite contractors to submit tenders for services.

Contractor
A contractor is an external service provider invited to submit quotations or tenders for providing services.

Quotation Exercise
The quotation exercise refers to the formal process of inviting, receiving, and evaluating quotations from contractors.

Appendix 4
Appendix 4 contains the Quotation/Tender Opening Record which details all quotations and tenders received.

Terms of Quotation
The Terms of Quotation are the rules and conditions that contractors must follow when submitting their quotations.

Sealed Envelope
A sealed envelope is required for submitting quotations, marked with the quotation reference for proper handling.

Fax Transmission
Fax transmission is an accepted method for submitting quotations to the specified fax number.

Quotation Reference Number
The quotation reference number is a unique identifier used to track and manage quotation submissions.

Quotation Closing Date
The quotation closing date is the deadline by which all quotations must be submitted to be considered.

Unit Price
Unit price refers to the cost per unit of service or item being quoted by the contractor.

Total Price
Total price is the overall cost calculated for the services being offered by the contractor.

Payment Terms
Payment terms specify the conditions under which the contractor will receive payment for services rendered.

Warranty of Service
Warranty of service refers to the guarantees and assurances provided by the contractor regarding service quality.

Open Tendering
Open tendering is a procurement method for services above a specified value, involving open invitation of tenders from contractors through public channels like websites or newspaper advertisements.

Restrictive Tendering
Restrictive tendering is a procurement method for services below a specified amount, involving invitation of a specified number of contractors from an approved list or the market.

Two-Envelope System
The two-envelope system is a procurement approach where contractors submit service and price proposals in separately sealed envelopes for assessment, used for high-value purchases where price is not the only consideration.

Conflict of Interest Declaration
Conflict of interest declaration requires staff involved in procurement to declare any perceived or actual conflicts, such as financial interests in tenderer businesses.<SEP>A process requiring individuals involved in procurement to declare any potential conflicts of interest.

Purchase Requisition Form
The Purchase Requisition Form is used to identify the need for cleaning or security services and draw up the required scope of service.<SEP>A form used to recommend a selected contractor, requiring endorsement from the approving authority and attachment of all received quotations.<SEP>Sample form used for making purchase requests for cleaning and security services.

Approving Authority
The approving authority endorses purchase requests, ascertains service needs, checks budgets, and approves procurement activities at appropriate levels.<SEP>The Approving Authority endorses procurement recommendations, evaluates final offers, and ensures compliance with selection criteria before contract award.

Approved Contractors List
The approved contractors list contains contractors approved by management for frequent cleaning and security service contracting exercises.

User
User identifies the need for cleaning or security services, draws up scope of service requirements, and submits purchase requisitions.<SEP>The User is involved in the procurement process, helping to check compliance with requirements and participating in the evaluation of tenders.

Cleaning Contracts
Cleaning contracts specify service requirements such as coverage, frequency of cleaning, number of workers, supervision plans, and response time for urgent tasks.<SEP>Service contracts for cleaning services that organizations outsource to contractors.<SEP>Cleaning Contracts are service agreements specifying cleaning schedules, worker headcounts, and standards of cleanliness, with performance monitored through surprise checks.

Security Contracts
Security contracts specify requirements including 24-hour coverage, guard posts, patrol frequency, security personnel numbers, equipment needs, and response times.<SEP>Service contracts for security services that organizations outsource to contractors.<SEP>Security Contracts are service agreements requiring specified guard posts, patrol frequencies, and security guard headcounts, monitored through electronic systems and surprise checks.

Tender/Quotation Document
Tender/quotation documents contain service specifications, background requirements, contract terms, payment methods, and selection criteria for bidders.

Duty Segregation
Duty segregation involves assigning different staff members to handle sourcing contractors, preparing service contracts, and monitoring service deliverables.

Quotations
Quotations are offers received from potential contractors during procurement, which must be properly recorded and evaluated for compliance and best price.

Tenders
Tenders are formal bids submitted by contractors, evaluated by a panel based on pre-determined criteria including price and quality of service.

Tender Evaluation Panel
The Tender Evaluation Panel is a group appointed to assess tenders based on pre-determined criteria, ensuring objectivity and fairness in the selection process.<SEP>The Tender Evaluation Panel is a group responsible for assessing and scoring submitted tenders based on predefined criteria.

Negotiation Team
The Negotiation Team conducts post-tender negotiations within defined parameters, documents proceedings, and seeks management instruction as needed.

Post-Tender Negotiation
Post-Tender Negotiation is a process conducted with selected tenderers to refine offers, guided by management-set parameters and resulting in a "best and final" offer.<SEP>The process of negotiating with tenderers after tender submission but before contract award.

Service Contracts
Service Contracts formalize agreements with contractors, detailing terms such as service standards, payment schedules, and probity clauses.

Tender Evaluation Form
A form designed for panel members to independently assess tenders before discussion, enhancing fairness and objectivity in scoring.<SEP>Sample form used for evaluating tenders submitted by contractors.<SEP>The Tender Evaluation Form is a document used by panel members to individually score and evaluate each tender.

Tender Evaluation Report
A report submitted by procurement staff recommending the best tender offer or suggesting post-tender negotiation, for endorsement by the approving authority.<SEP>Sample report used for documenting the evaluation results of tenders.<SEP>The Tender Evaluation Report summarizes the assessment process, compliance checks, and recommendations for tender awards.

Best and Final Offer
The final proposal submitted in writing by a bidder after post-tender negotiation, which is then evaluated by the tender evaluation panel.

Best Practice Checklist (BPC)
A user-friendly guide providing procedures and safeguards to prevent malpractice in the letting and administration of cleaning and security contracts.

ICAC (Independent Commission Against Corruption)
Hong Kong's anti-corruption agency that provides free, confidential corruption prevention advice to private companies.

Advisory Services Group
A group within ICAC's Corruption Prevention Department that offers tailored corruption prevention advice.

Corruption Prevention Department
The department within ICAC responsible for preventing corruption through advisory services.<SEP>The Corruption Prevention Department is part of the Independent Commission Against Corruption, located in Hong Kong.

Organizations/Companies
Entities that contract out cleaning and security services to external providers.

Contract Letting Process
The process of inviting, evaluating, and awarding service contracts to contractors.

Service Monitoring
The process of overseeing and evaluating contractor performance and service deliverables.

Quotation Invitation Form
Sample form used for inviting quotations from potential contractors.

Contractor Performance Evaluation Checklist
Sample checklist used for monitoring and evaluating contractor performance.<SEP>A standardized form used to assess contractor performance across various criteria including quality, timeliness, and responsiveness.

Management Supervision
Oversight and supervision by management throughout the contract administration process.

Tender
The Tender is a formal offer to provide goods or services at a specified price, which bidders agree to abide by for a set period.

Bidder/Tenderer
A Bidder or Tenderer is a company submitting a formal offer in response to a tender invitation.

Annex 3
Annex 3 is an attachment to the Tender Invitation Letter containing anti-bribery and anti-collusion clauses.<SEP>Annex 3 contains anti-bribery and anti-collusion clauses and confirmation letter requirements.

Witness
An individual who signs to verify the tender opening process, ensuring its integrity and transparency.

Assessment Panel
A group responsible for evaluating tenders, identifying strengths and weaknesses, and making recommendations for contract awards.<SEP>The Assessment Panel is responsible for evaluating tender submissions and making recommendations for contract awards.

Tender Specifications
The detailed requirements and conditions that tenders must comply with to be considered for evaluation.

Tender Qualifications
Additional conditions or clarifications submitted by a tenderer that may alter the original tender specifications.

User/Contract Administration Staff
User/Contract Administration Staff are responsible for monitoring contractor performance, conducting checks, reviewing deliverables, and processing payments.

Accounting Staff
Accounting Staff verify and process payment claims, ensure accuracy of supporting documents, and adhere to internal time limits for payment processing.

Performance Evaluation Checklist
The Performance Evaluation Checklist is a tool used to record and assess contractor performance, including adverse observations during site visits.

Probity Clause
The Probity Clause is a contract condition prohibiting contractors and their staff from offering, soliciting, or accepting bribes during contract performance.

Insurance Policies
Insurance Policies are required documents under the contract, providing coverage as specified in the agreement.

Attendance Records
Attendance Records are supporting documents required for payment claims, verifying the presence and work of contractor staff.

Invoices
Invoices are submitted by contractors as part of payment claims, detailing charges for services rendered.

Log Book
A Log Book is maintained by contractors to record all special or additional job orders, used for verification and payment certification.

Disciplinary Action
Disciplinary Action refers to procedures taken against contractors for breaches of contract or unsatisfactory performance, including payment deductions or contract termination.

Payment Claims
Payment Claims are requests submitted by contractors with supporting documents like invoices and attendance records, processed within specified time limits.

Surprise Checks
Surprise Checks are unannounced inspections conducted by User/Contract Administration Staff to verify contractor performance and compliance.

Tender Document
The Tender Document is an official invitation for tender issued by a company/organization for the provision of specific services, containing detailed requirements and submission guidelines.

Annex 1
Annex 1 contains the detailed specifications and schedule of services required for the tender.

Annex 2
Annex 2 lists the mandatory requirements and documents that tenderers must submit for eligibility evaluation.

Annex 4
Annex 4 is the Form of Tender document that must be completed by tenderers.

Prevention of Bribery Ordinance (Cap. 201)
The Prevention of Bribery Ordinance is the legal framework referenced in the anti-bribery clauses of the tender document.

Type of Services
The specific category of services required by the Company/Organization, to be detailed in the tender specifications.

Anti-Bribery and Anti-Collusion Clauses
Specific contractual provisions that tenderers must abide by to prevent corruption and collusion in the tendering process.

Business Registration Certificate
A mandatory document that tenderers must submit as proof of company registration.

ISO 9001 Certification
An optional quality assurance certification that tenderers may submit if available.

Company Code of Conduct
An optional document outlining staff conduct policies that tenderers may submit if available.

Complaints Handling Procedures
An optional document detailing complaint resolution processes that tenderers may submit if available.

Declaration of No Litigation
A mandatory declaration issued by a solicitor confirming no litigation for the past five years.

Company / Organization
The Company/Organization is the entity conducting the tender process and making contract award decisions.

Successful Tenderer
The successful tenderer is the company selected for contract award after the tender evaluation process.

Unsuccessful Tenderers
Unsuccessful tenderers are companies that submitted bids but were not selected for the contract award.

Independent Commission Against Corruption
An anti-corruption agency based in Hong Kong that includes the Corruption Prevention Department.

Tender Evaluation Process
The systematic process of assessing and comparing tender submissions to select the most suitable contractor.

Hong Kong
Hong Kong is the location where the Independent Commission Against Corruption and its Corruption Prevention Department are based.

303 Java Road, North Point
The specific address of the Independent Commission Against Corruption's Corruption Prevention Department in Hong Kong.

Tender Documents
Official documents prepared for the tender process that include specifications, requirements, and evaluation criteria.

Warning Letter
A formal document issued to contractors who perform poorly, indicating areas needing improvement.

Senior Management
Senior management personnel responsible for reviewing tender specifications and assessment results to detect favoritism.

Contract Award Decision
The final decision-making process for selecting which tenderer receives the contract.

Performance Rating System
A standardized rating system (0-4) used to evaluate contractor performance across multiple criteria.

Mobile Responsiveness
Mobile responsiveness is a specified requirement for the custom web application being developed.<SEP>Mobile responsiveness is a technical requirement ensuring the web application works on mobile devices.<SEP>Mobile responsiveness is a specified requirement for the custom web application.

Data Analytics Features
Data analytics features are specified components of the custom web application being developed.<SEP>Data analytics features are among the technical requirements specified for the web application.<SEP>Data analytics features are specified components of the custom web application.

Custom Web Application
The custom web application is the software product being developed, featuring user authentication, dashboard interface, data analytics, and mobile responsiveness.<SEP>A custom web application is the deliverable product being developed as part of the software development project.<SEP>A custom web application is the project deliverable, featuring user authentication, dashboard, analytics, and mobile responsiveness.

Software Development Agreement
The Software Development Agreement is a contract outlining terms for software development services between ABC Company and XYZ Corporation.<SEP>The agreement outlines terms for software development services between ABC Company and XYZ Corporation.

User Authentication System
The user authentication system is a specified feature of the custom web application being developed.<SEP>User authentication system is one of the technical specifications required in the web application.<SEP>User authentication system is a specified feature of the custom web application being developed.<SEP>A user authentication system is a specified feature of the custom web application.

Dashboard Interface
The dashboard interface is a specified feature of the custom web application being developed.<SEP>Dashboard interface is a specified feature component of the custom web application.<SEP>Dashboard interface is a specified feature of the custom web application being developed.<SEP>A dashboard interface is a specified feature of the custom web application.

ABC Company
ABC Company is the uploader company and a party to the Software Development Agreement for software development services.<SEP>ABC Company is a party to the software development agreement, receiving services from XYZ Corporation.

XYZ Corporation
XYZ Corporation is the other company party to the Software Development Agreement for software development services.<SEP>XYZ Corporation is a software development company providing services to ABC Company under the agreement.<SEP>XYZ Corporation is the other company and a party to the Software Development Agreement for software development services.<SEP>XYZ Corporation is a party providing software development services to ABC Company under the outlined agreement.

CONT_000001
CONT_000001 is the unique contract identifier for the Software Development Agreement.<SEP>CONT_000001 is the unique identifier for the Software Development Agreement contract.<SEP>CONT_000001 is the unique identifier for the Test Contract.

$75,000.00
$75,000.00 is the contract amount specified in the Software Development Agreement.<SEP>The contract amount of $75,000.00 represents the total financial value of the Software Development Agreement.

cross-company
Cross-company is the contract type indicating the agreement is between two different companies.

6 months
6 months is the estimated total project duration for the software development services.

Monthly Milestones
Monthly milestones are the progress tracking points specified in the Software Development Agreement.<SEP>Monthly milestones are the progress tracking mechanism specified in the development timeline.<SEP>Monthly milestones represent the project timeline structure with progress checkpoints throughout the six-month duration.<SEP>Monthly milestones are specified as part of the project timeline and progress tracking mechanism.

pending
Pending is the current status of the Software Development Agreement.

Test Document
The Test Document is the subject of the input text, which is described as a test document.<SEP>The Test Document is the subject of the input text, though no specific details about its content or purpose are provided.

Contract Analysis
Contract Analysis refers to the process of examining and evaluating the terms and conditions within a contract.

Test Contract
The Test Contract is the subject of analysis in the provided content.<SEP>Test Contract is a document with the ID CONT_000001 and a value of $50,000.00 for software development services.

Suspicious Words
Suspicious Words are terms or phrases that may indicate potential issues, risks, or anomalies within the analyzed text.

Text Analysis Content
Text Analysis Content refers to the process of examining text to identify specific elements or patterns.

Test document
The Test document is the input text being processed for entity and relationship extraction.<SEP>The Test document is used for verifying API connectivity and functionality.

Software Development Services
Software development services are the core subject of the agreement between ABC Company and XYZ Corporation.<SEP>Software Development Services are the subject and purpose of the Test Contract.

6-Month Project Duration
The project has an estimated total duration of six months as outlined in the agreement.<SEP>The total project duration is estimated at 6 months with monthly milestones.

Agreement
The agreement is the contract document outlining terms for software development services between ABC Company and XYZ Corporation.<SEP>The Agreement refers to the Terms and Conditions document, including any attached Schedules and mutually executed Service Orders, governing the relationship between Client and Provider.

Cross-Company Contract
The contract type is cross-company, indicating an agreement between two different companies.

Six-Month Project Duration
The project has an estimated duration of six months with monthly milestones.

Contract Title
Contract Title is a metadata field specifying the name of the document as "Test Contract".

Contract ID
Contract ID is a metadata field containing the unique identifier "CONT_000001" for the contract.

Contract Content
Contract Content is a metadata field describing the purpose of the contract as being for software development services.

$50,000.00
$50,000.00 is the monetary value specified in the Test Contract.

Contract Amount
Contract Amount is a metadata field specifying the monetary value of "$50,000.00" for the contract.

Connectivity Check
Connectivity Check refers to the process of verifying network or system connections, which is the purpose of the Test document.

API
API refers to Application Programming Interface, a set of protocols for building software applications.

Deliverables
Deliverables are the final outputs created specifically for Client, for which Provider grants a license upon full payment.

Client
Client is the individual or entity purchasing Services from Provider as defined in the Agreement.

Fees
Fees are the payments Client agrees to pay Provider as set forth in the Service Order for Services rendered.

Provider
Provider is the entity providing Services to Client as defined in the Agreement, specifically identified as [Your Company Name].

Service Order
Service Order is a mutually executed document that references the Terms and Conditions and describes specific Services to be provided.

Confidential Information
Confidential Information includes all non-public business, financial, technical, and operational information that both parties agree to protect.

Schedule
Schedule refers to any attached documents that form part of the Agreement along with the Terms and Conditions and Service Orders.

Material Breach
Material Breach is a significant violation of the Agreement that allows either party to terminate if not cured within thirty days after written notice.

Finance Charge
Finance Charge is a penalty fee applied to late payments, typically 1.5% per month or the maximum rate allowed by law.

Pre-Existing Intellectual Property
Pre-Existing Intellectual Property refers to intellectual property rights that each party owned before entering into the Agreement.

Client Materials
Client Materials include logos, data, and other materials provided by Client that Provider may use to perform the Services.

Governing Law
Governing Law specifies that the Agreement is governed by the laws of the State of [Your State/Province] without regard to conflict of laws principles.

Independent Contractor
Independent Contractor status clarifies that Provider is not an employee, agent, or partner of Client and is responsible for its own taxes and benefits.
